\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \u2013\n| 25 August || Devonport || LBD || City || WBD || Auckland Domain, 3pm\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Semi Final\n| 1 September <ref>{{cite news \n| title = Lower Grade Results\n| page =3\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXXI| issue=21895\n| date = 1934-09-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19340903.2.176.3\n| accessdate = 2019-10-02}}</ref>\n|| City|| 4 || Marist || 3 || Auckland Domain, 1:30pm\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Final\n| 8 September <ref name=\"final\" />\n|| Richmond|| 21 || City || 9 || Carlaw Park # 2\n|-\n|}\n\n==Other Club Matches and Lower Grades==\n===Lower Grade Clubs===\nDuring the middle part of the season the Junior Management Committee revised the weight allowances for the junior grades. They were Third Intermediate \u2013 10st 13lbs; Fourth Grade \u2013 9st, 13lbs; Fifth Grade \u2013 9st 6lbs; Sixth Grade \u2013 9st 3lbs; Seventh Grade \u2013 8st 10lb.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Junior Management/Weighted Grade Requirements\n| page =16\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=168\n| date = 1934-07-18\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340718.2.167\n| accessdate = 2019-12-12}}</ref>\nThe winning team in bold:\n*'''Second Grade''': Ellerslie, Mangere, Mount Albert, Otahuhu, Papakura, Point Chevalier\n*'''Third Grade Open''': Akarana, Glenora, Mangere, Marist, Mount Albert, Papakura, Ponsonby, Richmond\n*'''Third Grade Intermediate''': Akarana, City, Devonport, Glenora, Manukau A, Manukau B, Marist, Northcote, Otahuhu, Papakura, Point Chevalier, Ponsonby, Richmond\n*'''Fourth Grade''': Glenora, Ellerslie, Manukau, Marist, Newton, Northcote, Papakura, Point Chevalier, Richmond, \n*'''Fifth Grade''': City, Devonport, Manukau, Mount Albert, Otahuhu, Papakura, Point Chevalier, Ponsonby, Richmond\n*'''Sixth Grade''': Avondale, Devonport, Ellerslie, Newton, Point Chevalier, Richmond\n*'''Seventh Grade''': City, Devonport, Mount Albert, Northcote, Richmond A, Richmond B\n*'''Schoolboys''': Avondale, City, Devonport, Ellerslie, Marist A, Marist B, Northcote, Otahuhu, Richmond\n*'''Seven a-side''': Avondale, City, Devonport, Ellerslie, Marist A, Northcote\n\n===Other Notable Matches===\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\" | List of Matches\n|-\n|\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | \n! scope=\"col\" | Score\n! scope=\"col\" | \n! scope=\"col\" | Score\n! scope=\"col\" | Venue\n! scope=\"col\" | Attendance\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Exhibition Match\n| 30 June <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Curtain-Raiser Treat\n| page =13\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| issue=154\n| date = 1934-07-02\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340702.2.149\n| accessdate = 2019-12-05}}</ref>\n|| Mangere|| 11 || Tuakau || 12 || Carlaw Park # 1, 1:30pm\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Exhibition Match\n| 15 September <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Devonport Seniors Win/Defeat of North Auckland\n| page =7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXXI| issue=21908\n| date = 1934-09-18\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19340918.2.38.4\n| accessdate = 2020-01-19}}</ref>\n|| North Auckland|| 11 || Devonport || 17 ||Hikurangi \n|-\n|}\n\n==Representative Fixtures==\nThe first representative fixture of the season was played against Taranaki with L. Hutt being appointed captain. The Taranaki team was being picked by [[Frank Delgrosso]].\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\" | 1934 Auckland Representative Fixtures\n|-\n|\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | \n! scope=\"col\" | Score\n! scope=\"col\" | \n! scope=\"col\" | Score\n! scope=\"col\" | Venue\n! scope=\"col\" | Attendance\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Representative Fixture\n| 30 June <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Inter-Provincial Match\n| page =13\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| issue=154\n| date = 1934-07-02\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340702.2.149\n| accessdate = 2019-12-05}}</ref>\n|| Auckland || 35 || Taranaki || 8 || Carlaw Park # 1, 3pm\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Inter-Provincial\n| 11 August <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Auckland Wins League Rep. Match/Northland\u2019s Strong Bid/Conditions Deciding Factor\n| page = 16\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=190\n| date = 1934-08-13\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340813.2.153\n| accessdate = 2019-12-28}}</ref>\n|| Auckland || 19 || Northland || 12 || Carlaw Park # 1, 3pm\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | North Island v South Island\n| 1 September <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Victory to North/Inter-Island Rugby League/Souths Hold Interval Lead\n| page = 14\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=208\n| date = 1934-09-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340903.2.194\n| accessdate = 2020-01-19}}</ref>\n|| North Island || 36 || South Island || 18 || Carlaw Park, 3pm\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Waitangi Maori Shield\n| 12 September <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Tamaki Team Successful/Defeat of Lower Waikato\n| page =9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXXI| issue=21904\n| date = 1934-09-13\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19340913.2.38.4\n| accessdate = 2020-01-19}}</ref>\n|| Tamaki|| 36 || Lower Waikato || 13 || Carlaw Park\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Inter-Provincial\n| 15 September <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Auckland Defeats South/Visiting Team Weakened\n| page = 13\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXXI| issue=21907\n| date = 1934-09-17\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19340917.2.149.5\n| accessdate = 2020-01-19}}</ref>\n|| Auckland || 35 || South Auckland || 16 || Carlaw Park # 1, 3pm\n|-\n|}\n\n==Annual General Meetings and Club News==\n*[[Auckland Rugby League|Auckland Rugby League Junior Management Committee]] Mr. D Wilkie announced that Mr. T. Davis was resigning as secretary of the junior management after 8 years in the position. It was proposed that he be elected a life member of the Auckland Rugby League, an honour that had only been given to seven people to this point.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Senior Club Meetings\n| page = 19\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=51\n| date = 1934-03-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340301.2.163\n| accessdate = 2019-11-30}}</ref> The Primary Schools Committee announced that its officers were patron, Dr. Pezaro; president, Mr. R. E. Newport; and chairman, Mr. W. Stanley.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Board of Control Affairs\n| page = 18\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=97\n| date = 1934-04-26\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340426.2.170\n| accessdate = 2019-12-03}}</ref>\n\n*[[Auckland Rugby League|Auckland Rugby League Referees Association]] held their annual meeting on 19 March. There were over 40 members in attendance and the chairman Mr. A. Ball asked that his resignation be accepted after 11 years in that position and 20 in total as a member. Mr. L. E. Bull was elected president, Mr. A. McCowatt deputy chairman, and Mr. Simpson treasurer.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Referees\u2019 Annual Meeting/Chairman\u2019s Resignation\n| page = 13\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=67\n| date = 1934-03-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340320.2.143\n| accessdate = 2019-12-01}}</ref>\n\n*[[City Rovers|City Rovers Football Club]] held their general meeting at Carlaw Park on Tuesday 20 March at Carlaw Park.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =City Rovers\u2019 Football Club\n| page = 14\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=64\n| date = 1934-03-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340316.2.162.2\n| accessdate = 2019-12-01}}</ref> A good attendance was recorded and fourteen new members were elected, including four senior players. The financial statement showed a credit of \u00a370 and a profit on the season of over \u00a323. Mr. R. B. Ashby was elected patron, and Mr. L. McDonald the president.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =City Rovers Club\n| page = 19\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=69\n| date = 1934-03-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340322.2.163\n| accessdate = 2019-12-02}}</ref>\n\n*[[North Shore Albions|Devonport United]] held their annual meeting over Anthony\u2019s Tearooms, Devonport on Wednesday 21 March.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Devonport United League Football Club\n| page = 21\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=65\n| date = 1934-03-17\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340317.2.178.5\n| accessdate = 2019-12-01}}</ref> The meeting was presided over by Mr. Arch Ferguson and saw 80 members and supporters in attendance. The club had cash and assets amounting to \u00a359. Mr. A. W. D. Meiklejohn was elected patron, Mr. J. Donald president, and Mr. A. Ferguson vice-president. Mr. C. McSweeney donated a trophy to be used as the club decided and Mr. Wouldes donated one for the most improved senior player.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Devonport United Club\n| page = 18\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=71\n| date = 1934-03-24\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340324.2.139\n| accessdate = 2019-12-02}}</ref> At the Auckland Rugby League Board of Control meeting on 16 May [[North Shore Albions|Devonport]] applied for and were granted permission to play their match versus [[Richmond Bulldogs|Richmond]] on the North Shore in aid of the [[Noel Crump]] fund.<ref name=\"control_board\">{{cite news \n| title =Auckland Control Board\n| page = 18\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=115\n| date = 1934-05-17\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340517.2.167\n| accessdate = 2019-12-04}}</ref> He was raising funds to go to the [[1934 British Empire Games]] where he would later compete and win a bronze medal. Prior to the round 6 matches Devonport advised the league that Mr. A. Laing, sen., had been appointed coach and selector to succeed A. W. Seagar who would revert back to being a playing member only.<ref name=\"auck_treasurer\" />\n\n*[[Ellerslie Eagles|Ellerslie United League Football Club]] held their annual meeting at the Club\u2019s Training Shed, Findlay St, Ellerslie on Wednesday, 14 March.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Ellerslie United League Football Club\n| page = 19\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=59\n| date = 1934-03-10\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340310.2.193.8\n| accessdate = 2019-11-30}}</ref> There was a large attendance with the balance sheet shown to be in a satisfactory position. Mr. J. W. Jordan MP. was elected patron, Mr. J. McInnarny president, and Mr. F. Chapman club captain. Mr. G. Chapman, jun., was unanimously elected an honorary life member of the club.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Ellerslie United Club\n| page = 16\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=63\n| date = 1934-03-15\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340315.2.140\n| accessdate = 2019-12-01}}</ref> Proposals for the floodlighting of the Ellerslie Domain were discussed by the Ellerslie Domain Board and representatives of the local sports bodies on 15 May. It was recommended by the Auckland Electric-Power Board \u201cthat not less than two lights be installed. The Power Board would be prepared to install the lights for \u00a314 on condition that the Domain Board would undertake to pay a flat rate of \u00a32 15s per lamp per annum, inclusive of power and maintenance, and accept the arrangement for not less than five years\u201d.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Ellerslie Domain/Proposals for Lighting\n| page = 14\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXXI| issue=21801\n| date = 1934-05-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19340516.2.174\n| accessdate = 2019-12-16}}</ref>\n\n*[[Glenora Bears|Glenora Rugby League Football Club]] held their annual meeting at the Glen Eden Town Hall.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Glenora League Football Club\n| page = 20\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=50\n| date = 1934-02-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340228.2.216.7\n| accessdate = 2019-11-30}}</ref> A \u201cgood gathering of supporters and followers\u201d attended with Mr. A. J. Routley elected Patron, and Mr W. McNeil chairman.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Glenora Annual Meeting\n| page = 14\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=55\n| date = 1934-03-06\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340306.2.172\n| accessdate = 2019-11-30}}</ref> Trainings were being held at the Glen Eden Recreation Ground.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Glenora League Football\n| page = 20\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=62\n| date = 1934-03-14\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340314.2.193.1\n| accessdate = 2019-12-01}}</ref> Glenora requested that a referee be sent to their club to address the players on the finer points of play so the Auckland Rugby League Referees Association agreed to send Mr. S. Billman to visit the Glen Eden club.<ref name=\"affairs_refs\" /> The league made a special grant towards the Glenora club towards ground expenses. They advised the league that they had signed over 55 new players in the 1934 season and were making good progress in the Glen Eden district.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Control Board Affairs\n| page = 16\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXIV| issue=145\n| date = 1934-06-21\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340621.2.153\n| accessdate = 2019-12-05}}</ref>\n\n*[[Mangere Rugby League Football Club]] were asked to compel spectators to stand back on the bank at games staged in Mangere.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Junior Board Affairs\n| page = 15\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=144\n| date = 1934-06-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340620.2.151\n| accessdate = 2019-12-05}}</ref>\n\n*[[Manukau Magpies|Manukau League Football Club]] held their annual meeting in Kelvin Hall, Queen Street, Onehunga on Monday, 19 March.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Manukau League Football Club\n| page = 21\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=65\n| date = 1934-03-17\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340317.2.178.5\n| accessdate = 2019-12-01}}</ref> The Onehunga Borough Council at a meeting on 3 April stated that the Manukau league club could use its recreation reserve provided it laid a portion of the concrete floor in its new shed, and a water meter was installed.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Onehunga Council\n| page = 3\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=79\n| date = 1934-04-04\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340404.2.21\n| accessdate = 2019-12-02}}</ref> On 14 April a \u201cBig Maori Carnival and Athletic Sports\u201d event was held at the Onehunga Recreation Ground. It included senior league matches.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Big Maori Carnival and Athletic Sports\n| page = 14\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=87\n| date = 1934-04-13\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340413.2.181.7\n| accessdate = 2019-12-02}}</ref> After the 30 June round of matches a member mentioned at a Board of Control meeting that facilities continued to be lacking at the Manukau ground with no lines being marked, no flags, and the goal posts were down at one end. The match still took place anyway.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Affairs of Referees\n| page = 14\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=155\n| date = 1934-07-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340703.2.155\n| accessdate = 2019-12-06}}</ref>\n\n*[[Marist Saints|Marist Brothers Old Boys League Football Club]] held their annual meeting in the League Rooms, Courthouse Lane on Thursday 22, March.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Marist Old Boys\u2019 Rugby League Football Club\n| page = 18\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=67\n| date = 1934-03-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340320.2.168.3\n| accessdate = 2019-12-01}}</ref> Nearly one hundred members were in attendance to hear that the club was in a healthy financial position. Reverend Dr. Liston, Bishop of Auckland was elected patron, Mr. E. Lahman president, and Mr. J. Kirwan secretary.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Marist Old Boys\u2019 Club\n| page = 10\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=70\n| date = 1934-03-23\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340323.2.154\n| accessdate = 2019-12-02}}</ref> Marist advertised for a special general meeting to be held at the Chamber of Commerce rooms on Swanson Street on Monday, 28.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Marist Old Boys Club\n| page = 20\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=121\n| date = 1934-05-24\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340524.2.170\n| accessdate = 2019-12-04}}</ref> It turned out that the voting at their original meeting was declared void as unqualified members had voted. Mr. Cyril Sneddon, the president of New Zealand Rugby League was invited to attend and the following officers were elected: patron, Reverend Dr. Liston; president, Mr. J. Sayegh; club captain, Mr. H. Brisbane; hon secretary, Mr. J. Kirwan; Mr. O. Robertson.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Marist O.B. Club/Annual Meeting Re-Held\n| page = 13\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=125\n| date = 1934-05-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340529.2.131\n| accessdate = 2019-12-04}}</ref> In round 6 eight of the senior Marist players (W. Hassan, C. Dunn, D. Herring, the 3 Shultz brothers, and C. list) refused to appear. They were in a dispute with the club over \u201cwhether a porting of expenditure should apply to senior players alone or be devoted to general club services, including juniors\u201d. Despite fielding many juniors the team still won their match. Hassan transferred to the rugby code and played for Marist rugby club the following weekend.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Football Dispute/Marist League Club\n| page = 3\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=134\n| date = 1934-06-08\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340608.2.14\n| accessdate = 2019-12-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite news \n| title =Marist Club Overruled\n| page = 16\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXIV| issue=145\n| date = 1934-06-21\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340621.2.153\n| accessdate = 2019-12-05}}</ref> The Marist club tried to suspend the players involved but the New Zealand Rugby League Council said that the players in question could apply for transfers to other clubs. Marist appealed this decision and when four of the players did apply for transfers the Marist club refused this.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Auckland Affairs/Successful Junior Appeal/Marist Club Repercussions\n| page = 17\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=157\n| date = 1934-07-05\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340705.2.134\n| accessdate = 2019-12-06}}</ref>\n\n*[[Mt Albert Lions|Mt. Albert United Rugby League Football Club]] held their annual meeting in the King George Hall, Mt Albert Terminus on Thursday, 8 March.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =The Mount Albert United Rugby Football Club\n| page = 18\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=55\n| date = 1934-03-06\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340306.2.215.4\n| accessdate = 2019-11-30}}</ref> It was their sixth annual meeting and it was commented by the president Mr. J. Eccles that the club was in a sound financial position. The Mayor of Mount Albert Mr. Ferner was elected Patron, Mr. A. S. Richards M.P. was elected vice-patron, Mr. J. Eccles president, and Mr. R. Wilson secretary and treasurer. Mr. W. F. Clarke who had held office for the first six years of the club tendered his resignation and as a mark of appreciation was elected a life member.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Mount Albert Club\n| page = 11\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=58\n| date = 1934-03-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340309.2.146\n| accessdate = 2019-11-30}}</ref> They held their annual practice at Fowld\u2019s Park, Morningside on 7 April. Prior to this in previous seasons they had held practices and games at the ground at Springleigh Ave and at Fowld\u2019s Park which had previously been known as Morningside Reserve but in July 1933 was renamed Fowld\u2019s Park in honour of the honourable Sir George Fowlds.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Fowld\u2019s Park\n| page = 6\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXIV| issue=168\n| date = 1934-07-19\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19330719.2.61\n| accessdate = 2019-12-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite news \n| title =Mt. Albert United Rugby League Football Club\n| page = 22\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=80\n| date = 1934-04-05\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340405.2.173.3\n| accessdate = 2019-12-02}}</ref> A special general meeting was to be held at Fowld\u2019s Park on Saturday, 21 April regarding the changing of the club\u2019s colours.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Mt. Albert United Rugby League Football Club\n| page = 24\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=92\n| date = 1934-04-19\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340419.2.186.3\n| accessdate = 2019-12-02}}</ref>\n\n*New Lynn Rugby League Football Club held a special meeting at the Old Post Office, Totara Avenue on 22 March.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =League Football, Special Meeting\n| page = 18\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=68\n| date = 1934-03-21\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340321.2.173.1\n| accessdate = 2019-12-02}}</ref>\n\n*[[Newton Rangers|Newton Rangers Football Club]] held their annual meeting at Grey\u2019s Buildings, Courthouse Lane on Monday 12 March.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Newton Rangers Football Club\n| page = 19\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=53\n| date = 1934-03-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340303.2.180.5\n| accessdate = 2019-11-30}}</ref> The meeting was presided over by Mr. E. W. Taylor with over seventy members and supporters in attendance. Mr. D. Wilkie, chairman of the junior management committee was also in attendance. Their report touched on the playing improvement of the previous season and the balance sheet showed a credit of \u00a319 10/. Mr. Matt. Hooper was elected patron, Mr W. Monteith vice-patron, and Mr. J. A. Lee MP president. Notably Mr. P. Henry was elected treasurer for the 17th year.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Newton Rangers\u2019 Club\n| page = 13\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=61\n| date = 1934-03-13\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340313.2.132\n| accessdate = 2019-12-01}}</ref> Mr. A. J. McGregor (\u201cDugie\u201d) was unanimously elected as the sole selector and coach of the senior team with Mr. A. McLeod to fill the same role for the reserve team. Mr. A Middleton was chosen as the trainer and Mr. Turner the property steward. Before the season started the secretary received a cablegram suggesting that Roy Hardgrave would be returning to New Zealand to play for his old club. He left Newton to go and play for St. Helens in England in 1929 and had spent five seasons there.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Contract Ended/Footballer\u2019s Return\n| page = 8\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=67\n| date = 1934-03-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340320.2.104\n| accessdate = 2019-12-01}}</ref> He arrived back in Auckland on 25 June aboard the Aorangi with his wife and four year old daughter. He was met at the wharf by players and officials of the Newton club.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Footballer\u2019s Return/Roy Hardgrave Back/Keen to Play in Auckland\n| page = 9\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=148\n| date = 1934-06-25\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340625.2.124\n| accessdate = 2019-12-05}}</ref> A \u201cWelcome Home\u201d dance was held for Hardgrave by the Newton club with over 500 people in attendance.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Newton Rangers Club/Welcome Home to Hardgrave\n| page = 14\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=150\n| date = 1934-06-27\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340627.2.129\n| accessdate = 2019-12-05}}</ref> During the season several prominent Newton players were granted transfers to Mt Albert and this was appealed by the Newton club, though the New Zealand Rugby League Council heard the case and dismissed it.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Appeal Dismissed\n| page = 9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXXI| issue=21887\n| date = 1934-08-24\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19340824.2.32.9\n| accessdate = 2020-01-19}}</ref>\n\n*[[Northcote Tigers|Northcote and Birkenhead Ramblers Football Club]] held their annual meeting at the Buffalo\u2019s Hall, Northcote on Tuesday 13 March.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Rugby League\n| page = 16\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXXI| issue=21746\n| date = 1934-03-10\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19340310.2.179.2\n| accessdate = 2019-11-30}}</ref> The Northcote Borough Council granted the use of the municipal ground at Stafford Park to the Northcote Rugby League team and the Northcote rugby team on alternate Saturday\u2019s.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Northcote Borough Council\n| page = 11\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=74\n| date = 1934-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340328.2.120\n| accessdate = 2019-12-02}}</ref>\n\n*[[Otahuhu Leopards|Otahuhu Rugby League Football Club]] held their annual meeting in the local Gas Company\u2019s hall. The balance-sheet showed that the club was in a sound financial position. [[Walter William Massey|Mr. W. W. Massey, MP]] was elected patron, Mr. J. Nicholson elected president, and Mr. J. Clark elected chairman.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Otahuhu Club\n| page = 16\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=63\n| date = 1934-03-15\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340315.2.140\n| accessdate = 2019-12-01}}</ref> On 5 July the Otahuhu Borough Council\u2019s parks committee reported that it had awarded a contract to install floodlights at a cost of \u00a350 at Sturgess Park. The Otahuhu league club had been given use of the park along with the Otahuhu rugby club, and they tended to alternate the use of it. Both clubs were given permission to collect a charge from spectators on two upcoming match days each provided that the proceeds of one day are divided between the parks committee and charity.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Local Bodies/Otahuhu\n| page = 3\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=158\n| date = 1934-07-06\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340706.2.30\n| accessdate = 2019-12-06}}</ref>\n\n*[[Papakura Sea Eagles|Papakura Rugby League Football Club]] They applied for use of Prince Edward Park for the upcoming season and the Papakura Town Board asked for tenders for use of the ground.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Papakura\n| page = 9\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=49\n| date = 1934-02-27\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340227.2.139\n| accessdate = 2019-11-30}}</ref> The chairman of the reserves committee, Mr. G. W. Kerr said that the previous season two applications had been received for the use of the ground and the board had difficulty in deciding which application to grant.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Papakura Interests/Lease of Playing Area/Tenders to be Called\n| page = 5\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXXI| issue=21736\n| date = 1934-02-27\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19340227.2.21\n| accessdate = 2019-11-30}}</ref> The decision was eventually made for them when no other tenderers came forward and the ground was granted to Papakura Rugby League for \u201ctwo guineas for Saturday play\u201d.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Papakura Town Board\n| page = 3\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=61\n| date = 1934-03-13\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340313.2.17\n| accessdate = 2019-12-31}}</ref> The club was concerned about loss of junior clubs best players to the senior grade clubs.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Papakura Club\n| page = 19\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=51\n| date = 1934-03-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340301.2.163\n| accessdate = 2019-11-30}}</ref> At their annual meeting which was held on 1 March Mr. S. H. Godden was in the chair and Mr. E. C. Foote was elected Patron, and Godden was elected President.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Papakura Football\n| page = 10\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=52\n| date = 1934-03-02\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340302.2.146\n| accessdate = 2019-11-30}}</ref> In mid April the Papakura club advised Auckland Rugby League that Mr. T. Harrison had been appointed to its committee, other officers appointed were G. Wilton as chairman, A. L. Lewis as secretary, and V. Ashby as treasurer.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Junior Management\n| page = 14\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=91\n| date = 1934-04-18\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340418.2.137\n| accessdate = 2019-12-02}}</ref> The balance sheet showed a small credit. Their annual report stated that they had a membership of 70 and had 23 honorary members.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Papakura Club\u2019s Officers\n| page = 9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXXI| issue=21740\n| date = 1934-03-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19340303.2.39.4\n| accessdate = 2019-11-30}}</ref> The New Zealand Herald reported on the Round 1 Second Grade match between Papakura and Ellerslie, played at Prince Edward Park. The match was won by Papakura 11\u20130.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Play at Papakura\n| page = 13\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXXI| issue=21793\n| date = 1934-05-07\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19340507.2.157.2\n| accessdate = 2019-12-03}}</ref> Mr. Billman from the Referees Association reported that there were 79 players and officials at a training night that he had been requested to attend. He said it was a pleasure to note the enthusiasm display.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Affairs of Referees\n| page = 14\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=149\n| date = 1934-06-26\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340626.2.154\n| accessdate = 2019-12-05}}</ref> On 30 June the fifth grade teams bus broke down on the way to Victoria Park and the match was called off and awarded to Ponsonby. After the reason for their late arrival was explained it was decided to replay the match at a later date.<ref name=\"jb_affairs\" />\n\n*[[Point Chevalier Pirates|Point Chevalier League Football Club]] held their annual meeting at the Point Chevalier Sailing Club Hall on Wednesday, 21 March.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Pt. Chevalier League Football Club\n| page = 21\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=65\n| date = 1934-03-17\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340317.2.178.5\n| accessdate = 2019-12-01}}</ref>\n\n*[[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United Football Club]] held their 23rd annual meeting at Leys Institute, Ponsonby on Tuesday 6 March.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Annual Meeting, Ponsonby United Football Club\n| page = 20\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=50\n| date = 1934-02-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340228.2.216.7\n| accessdate = 2019-11-30}}</ref> The 24th report in the clubs history was submitted and stated that despite some misfortunes the senior team was very young and showed promising signs especially under the coaching of ex-international [[Frank Delgrosso]]. Brian Riley won an award for the most improved back, and L. Hutt was chosen as the best forward. The club had suffered a financial loss for the 1933 season but had been able through its credit building fund to advance a loan to the Auckland Rugby League of \u00a3150 to assist in the grandstand development scheme at Carlaw Park. They elected Mr. A. H. McKeown as patron, Mr. S. McDonald as president, and Mr. C. J. W. Taylor as treasurer.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Ponsonby United Club\n| page = 10\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=80\n| date = 1934-04-06\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340406.2.129\n| accessdate = 2019-12-02}}</ref> At the 16 May Board of Control meeting of Auckland Rugby League Ponsonby notified them that Mr. L. Riley, the international player had become a coach at Northcote, and that Mr. A. Philburn had been appointed to the Ponsonby Club committee in succession to Mr. R. Allen.<ref name=\"control_board\" />\n\n*[[Richmond Bulldogs|Richmond Rovers Football Club]] held their annual meeting at the Gaiety Hall, Surrey Crescent on Monday 5 March.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Richmond Rovers Football Club\n| page = 19\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=53\n| date = 1934-03-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340303.2.180.5\n| accessdate = 2019-11-30}}</ref> There was a large attendance of players and members with the annual report and balance sheet showing that the club was in a sound financial position. Mr. W. J. Holdsworth was elected Patron, Mr. B. W. Davis president, and Mr. W. A. Swift chairman. Mr. Davis was celebrating his 21st year with the club and it was proposed to mark the occasion with a presentation. There were 28 new playing members registered during the evening.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Richmond Rovers Club\n| page = 14\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=55\n| date = 1934-03-06\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340306.2.172\n| accessdate = 2019-11-30}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.aucklandleague.co.nz/ Auckland Rugby League Official Site]\n\n[[Category:Auckland Rugby League seasons]]\n[[Category:Rugby league in Auckland]]\n[[Category:Rugby league governing bodies in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Rugby league]]\n", "text_old": "The 1934 [[Auckland Rugby League]] season was its 26th. The senior championship was won by [[Richmond Bulldogs|Richmond Rovers]] who ran away with the title with an 11 win, 2 loss record. Such was their dominance that the league didn't bother playing the 14th round as Richmond had a 6-point lead over their nearest competitor. The Richmond reserve grade team also won the title which was remarkable in that they lost their first two matches before reeling off 12 consecutive wins to claim the title. They also won the Roope Rooster knockout competition with a 20 to 13 win over [[Marist Saints|Marist Old Boys]]. Richmond's remarkable season also included the Stormont Shield which they won 21 to 5 over [[Newton Rangers]], while their reserve grade team also won the Stallard Cup knockout competition when they beat [[City Rovers|City Rovers Reserves]] 21 to 9. Richmond also recorded two wins over the touring [[West Tigers|Western Suburbs]] side who had won the New South Wales premiership with 18-16 and 10-3 point wins. This was arguably the strongest set of results of any club at the senior level in Auckland Rugby League's history to this point.\n\nThe Roope Rooster competition saw the debut of the [[Mt Albert Lions|Mt Albert]] and [[Papakura Sea Eagles|Papakura]] senior teams playing in a senior A grade competition with both sides playing on [[Carlaw Park]] # 2 field. Both teams performed meritoriously before Mt Albert went down to Ponsonby 19 to 11, and Papakura lost to Marist 6 points to 3.\n\nThe [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] representative team had a successful season recording wins over [[Taranaki rugby league team|Taranaki]] by 35 to 8, [[Northland rugby league team|Northland]] 19 to 12, and South Auckland by 36 to 16. The season also saw the first ever match for an official Auckland M\u0101ori team which played under the name Tamaki. They hosted [[Waikato rugby league team|Lower Waikato]] in a Waitangi Maori Shield match which they won 36 to 13.\n\n==Auckland Rugby League Meetings==\nAt the annual meeting of the junior management committee on March 20 the report they received showed that the number of players and clubs had increased by over 11 percent and 14 percent respectively. The registration fees were an increase on 1932 by \u00a312 4/6. Mr. D. Wilkie was elected chairman, Mr. E. Chapman deputy chairman, while Mr. Mr. W. F. Clarke elected secretary to replace the long serving and retiring Mr. T. R. Davis.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Junior Management/Annual Meeting Business\n| page = 15\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=68\n| date = 1934-03-21\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340321.2.158\n| accessdate = 2019-12-02}}</ref> Davis was later appointed as a life member of New Zealand Rugby League, as was Arthur Ball (ex-chairman of the Auckland Rugby League Referees\u2019 Association, and C. Adamson (ex-chairman of the Junior Management Committee).<ref name=\"annual_meeting\">{{cite news \n| title =Council\u2019s Annual Meeting\n| page = 12\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=98\n| date = 1934-04-27\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340427.2.152\n| accessdate = 2019-12-03}}</ref>\n\nThe annual meeting of the [[Auckland Rugby League]] was held in the League Rooms, Grey Buildings, on Monday, April 9.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Annual Meeting of the Auckland Rugby League\n| page = 22\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=80\n| date = 1934-04-05\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340405.2.173.3\n| accessdate = 2019-12-02}}</ref> The report showed that the balance-sheet figures were improved on the previous season. \u201cThe principal of sharing the gate receipts with the clubs competing... has without doubt proved very beneficial in creating the team spirit to improve the standard of play required for No. 1 ground qualification each week-end and also has been reflected in a greater esprit de corps amongst club members, as well as a correspondingly enhanced friendly rivalry between the contestants that in turn excites public patronage to Carlaw Park\u201d. The gate takings were over \u00a3400 being available as grants to senior clubs in 1933. The working gate takings were \u00a31,953 12/9 from club matches (an increase of \u00a3158). Ground rents of \u00a3154 7/ were lower but profits of \u00a3196 18/ were recorded from matches with visiting provincial teams. Registered player fees accounted for \u00a399 12/ and this combined with donations and the earlier stated income meant total receipts of \u00a32,636 2/5. Expenditure was \u00a3487 17/6 on ground rents, \u00a3340 17/2 on maintenance and upkeep of the park and grounds, \u00a3175 on staffing grounds and cost to officials, and minor expenses. This meant a balance of \u00a321 4\u20198 to be carried forward. The profit and loss account showed a surplus of assets valued at \u00a36,415 19/7. Reference was also made to the services of George Rhodes who had passed away at the end of the 1933 season after many years as chairman of the league.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Rugby League/Game in Auckland/Last Season Reviewed\n| page = 16\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=82\n| date = 1934-04-07\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340407.2.125\n| accessdate = 2019-12-02}}</ref> At the annual meeting the following officers were elected: patron, Mr. J. B. Donald; vice-patron, Mr. J. F.W. Dickson; president, Mr. J. Carlaw; vice-presidents, Messrs. O. Blackwood; H. Grange; W. Wallace, C. Seagar, R. Benson, C.H. Drysdale, A.E. Laird, J.A. Lee, R.H. Wood, R.T. Sharman, J. Donald, J. Sayegh, J. Lovatt, W.S. Shramm, E. Morton, H. Walmsley, C. Wright, Montgomery and Bagnall; deputy-chairman, [[Ted Phelan|Mr. E.J. Phelan]]; hon. Secretary, Mr. I. Culpan; hon treasurer, Mr. J.E. Knowling; delegate to New Zealand Rugby League, Mr. R. Doble; auditor, Mr. R.A. Spinley; hon solicitor, Mr. H.M. Rogerson; referees\u2019 delegate on management committee, Mr. W. Mincham; club delegates, Mr [[Jim Rukutai]] and J.W. Probert; hon physicians, Drs. R. Tracey Inglis, Mr. G. Pezaro, F.J. Gwynne and K.H. Holdgate; press steward, Mr. R. Doble; board of control, Messrs. Campbell Rukutai, Doble, L. Binns, Probert, Mincham, D. Wilkie, Ellis, Knowling and I. Cuplan; trustees, Messrs. J. Stormont, [[Ted Phelan|E.J. Phelan]], and G. Grey Campbell.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Annual Meeting/Successful Past Season/Prospects for the Future\n| page =13 \n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=84\n| date = 1934-04-10\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340410.2.145\n| accessdate = 2019-12-02}}</ref>\n\nAt a board of control meeting in April it was decided that unemployed patrons would be admitted to [[Carlaw Park]] with the same concession as the previous season provided they produced their levy book regularly and it was stamped by the Labour Department. At the same meeting the Mt Albert Lions applied to have their colours changed from mauve to blue and gold. This was referred to the junior management committee.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Board of Control Affairs/Unemployed Concession Retained\n| page = 18\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=97\n| date = 1934-04-26\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340426.2.170\n| accessdate = 2019-12-03}}</ref>\n\n==Rules==\nIt was reported that in the latest English rule book there was a goal line drop out being taken when teams forced the ball in their own in goal area. It was decided that New Zealand would also adopt the rule.<ref name=\"annual_meeting\" /> It was decided to implement the rule at the start of the second round. It was eventually established after clarifying the interpretation of the law in England that the attacking team needed to stand five yards from the goal-line when the defending side drops the ball out from between its posts.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Force-Down Rule/English Interpretation Adopted\n| page = 13\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=122\n| date = 1934-05-25\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340525.2.133\n| accessdate = 2019-12-04}}</ref>\n\nContinued dissatisfaction was felt around the policing of the play the ball which caused problems. And late tacking was also said to be spoiling play. The referee committee said at their May 21 meeting that they intended to take drastic action on this matter.<ref name=\"affairs_refs\">{{cite news \n| title =Affairs of Referees\n| page = 15\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=119\n| date = 1934-05-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340522.2.158\n| accessdate = 2019-12-04}}</ref> At the Auckland Rugby League Board of Control meeting on May 23 chairman Campbell drew attention to the practice of players charging into opponents and using their knees. He said it was a serious offence, not a tackle and not football at all. The referees association took up the matter and said that all senior clubs would be written to and told that such conduct would not be tolerated.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Board of Control\n| page = 20\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=121\n| date = 1934-05-24\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340524.2.170\n| accessdate = 2019-12-04}}</ref> As a result of a large number of matches which were late kicking off due to teams arriving late or match officials arriving late or not at all the league pointed out \u201cthat a visiting team could be granted a 15-minute concession in starting and the length of spells could be reduced to 35 minutes each way by mutual agreement between the captains\u201d.<ref name=\"jb_affairs\">{{cite news \n| title =Junior Board Affairs\n| page = 17\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=156\n| date = 1934-07-04\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340704.2.162\n| accessdate = 2019-12-06}}</ref>\n\n==The Senior Competition==\nIt was decided that the championship would commence on April 28 and consist of three rounds. However the [[Auckland Rugby League]] would reserve the right to select the four leading teams to hasten the find for the champions if necessary.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Board of Control\n| page = 18\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=86\n| date = 1934-04-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340412.2.156\n| accessdate = 2019-12-02}}</ref> The league promoted the senior competition by taking the unusual approach of naming all the senior coaches and including boastful quotes from each of them in its newspaper advertisements. The add went \u201cWhat the Coaches say: Lar Seagar: Devonport will again be Champion and Champion of Champions. [[Thomas McClymont|Scotty McClymont]]: Richmond will be hard. The Rooster will be a Champion this year. [[Dougie McGregor|Duggie McGregor]]: Nothing can stop Newton winning. Pope Gregory: Marist O.B. will win from the start. The team is in great heart. [[Frank Delgrosso]]: Ponsonby wil this year produce the finest League team for many a day. [[Ben Davidson (rugby league)|Ben Davidson]]: City Rovers will be the sensation of the season. A team of All Blacks\u201d.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =League Football\n| page = 16\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=98\n| date = 1934-04-27\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340427.2.197.1\n| accessdate = 2019-12-03}}</ref> Newton, Richmond, and Ponsonby all sported new uniforms which were well received after their opening matches.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =League Football/Auckland Championship/Opening of 1934 Season/Wins by City, Ponsonby and Richmond. The opening round also saw the best opening day crowd for five years\n| page = 14\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=100\n| date = 1934-04-30\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340430.2.154\n| accessdate = 2019-12-03}}</ref>\n\nAt its weekly meeting the Board of Control banned metal sprigs after the Newton clubs officials and players complained \u201cstrongly\u201d against their use.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Control Board Affairs/Metal Boot Sprigs Prohibited\n| page = 21\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=169\n| date = 1934-07-19\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340719.2.156\n| accessdate = 2019-12-12}}</ref>\n\n==Carlaw Park==\nA new stand was planned for [[Carlaw Park]] to be built prior to the \u201cnext winter season\u201d. It would cost \u00a33,000 and have \u201cconcrete foundations and built in wood\u201d. Preliminary architectural plans were submitted by Mr Piper and Mr. Brooker. \u201cThe new stand while embracing the present stand, which would harmonise with the main design, will provide seating accommodation for from 2,500 to 3,000 people. It will incorporate the latest facilities for public and players. Teams will take the field from under the central part of the stand\u201d.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Carlaw Park/New Grandstand/Erection for Next Season/Support of Clubs\n| page = 8\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=43\n| date = 1934-02-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340220.2.98\n| accessdate = 2019-11-30}}</ref> The stands would also feature a large room for each senior club \u201cfitted with lockers, and hot and cold showers would be a feature of the dressing rooms, which will be built under the stand. Conveniences for the general public will also be provided\u201d. The present grandstand would be renovated and the new build would have \u201cglass fronts and sides, to protect spectators from the wet weather... the work is to be commenced immediately, and it may be completed within two weeks of the opening of the 1934 season\u201d.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =New Grandstand/Carlaw Park Structure/Facilities for New Season\n| page = 10\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXXI| issue=21731\n| date = 1934-02-21\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19340221.2.102\n| accessdate = 2019-11-30}}</ref> Work started on the new grandstand on March 9 after the plans and specifications were \u201cperused by the Auckland City Council, which proposed several alterations with a view to improvement of the building\u201d. The changes were accepted by the trustees of the Auckland Rugby League but it would mean in increase in the contract price to a little over \u00a33,000. It was aimed to complete the contract in May. [[Ted Phelan|Mr. E. J. Phelan]], a trustee and vice chairman of Auckland Rugby League announced that the successful tenderer was Mr. R. A. Cornish of Newmarket. The architects were Mr. L. S. Piper and Mr. L. E. Brooker who had submitted the initial plans.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Carlaw Park/Grandstand Enterprise/Work Starts To-Morrow\n| page = 9\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=57\n| date = 1934-03-08\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340308.2.101\n| accessdate = 2019-11-30}}</ref> By March 15 excavation works had been undertaken and were near completion. The board inspected them on March 16.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Board of Control/Carlaw Park Improvement\n| page = 16\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=63\n| date = 1934-03-15\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340315.2.140\n| accessdate = 2019-12-01}}</ref> Ponsonby donated \u00a3150 and it was hoped at the annual meeting that other clubs would also contribute \u00a350 each towards the costs. On the 21st of April the league arranged practice matches at Carlaw Park with the main match being between Marist and Ponsonby with those teams reserve grade sides playing the curtain-raiser. A charge of sixpence admission would go towards the grandstand funds which was expected to be completed by the following week.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Practice Games To-morrow\n| page = 11\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=93\n| date = 1934-04-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340420.2.135\n| accessdate = 2019-12-02}}</ref> Ponsonby defeated Marist by 13\u20130. The stand ultimately cost \u00a33,500 and as it neared completion the New Zealand Herald published a photograph of it.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Improvements at Carlaw Park\n| page = 7\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=99\n| date = 1934-04-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340428.2.27.3\n| accessdate = 2019-12-03}}</ref> In order to further help pay for the new stand the league sold 300 season tickets to the new stand which would entitle the purchaser to attend all matches under the control of the Auckland Rugby League this year. The tickets would cost \u00a31 each.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Special Notice!/Carlaw Park Grandstand\n| page = 22\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=103\n| date = 1934-05-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340503.2.190.4\n| accessdate = 2019-12-03}}</ref> A third unanimous offer of \u00a3100 was received from a supporter of the code which was gratefully accepted at the Board of Control meeting on May 9. The new grandstand was to be opened on Saturday May 12 by Governor-General, [[Charles Bathurst, 1st Viscount Bledisloe|Lord Bledisloe]] and the clubs.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Auckland Control Board/Opening New Grandstand/Arrangements for Saturday\n| page = 22\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=109\n| date = 1934-05-10\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340510.2.198\n| accessdate = 2019-12-04}}</ref>\n\nOn May 12 the new grandstand was officially opened by Lord Bledisloe in front of 17,000 spectators which was a record for a club match.<ref name=\"league_grandstand\">{{cite news \n| title =League Grandstand/Official Opening/Lord Bledisloe Officiates/Value of Healthy Sport\n| page = 10\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXXI| issue=21799\n| date = 1934-05-14\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19340514.2.119\n| accessdate = 2019-12-04}}</ref> Following the matches the six senior and six reserve teams \u201ctook up their respective club quarters in the new grandstand... and were delighted with the improved facilities. The Ponsonby Boys\u2019 Band played at the park and the pavilion was thrown open for public inspection\u201d.<ref name=\"auck_champs\">{{cite news \n| title =Auckland Championship/Richmond Rovers in Front/Second Wins to City and Newton\n| page = 13\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=112\n| date = 1934-05-14\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340514.2.134.1\n| accessdate = 2019-12-04}}</ref> Lord Bledisloe had said when opening the new stand that \u201che had always been a firm believer in the advantages of football, both as a means of developing physique, and in forming character and a sense of discipline. Some 24 years ago on the area which was now Carlaw Park the Chinese, he understood, had cultivated vegetables; to-day the ground was in use for the cultivation of sport and of health and character, which flowed from sport when conducted fairly, honestly and in a spirit of unselfishness. Congratulating the League organisation on its enterprise Lord Bledisloe ventured the hope that the sport would continue and flourish, and be maintained in New Zealand for many years to come\u201d. He went on to say that the \u201cerection of the new pavilion had provided useful work for about 60 men... and was built of good New Zealand rimu timber.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Opening of Stand/Lord Bledisloe\u2019s Praise/Tribute to Enterprise\n| page = 13\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=112\n| date = 1934-05-14\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340514.2.134.2\n| accessdate = 2019-12-04}}</ref>\n\nIn spite of the new stand and facilities the league still received a letter from [[Ellerslie Eagles|Ellerslie United]] complaining about the inadequate shower facilities at the ground.<ref name=\"jb_affairs\" />\n\n==Chairman Campbell's Sydney Visit==\nMr. G. Grey Campbell, chairman of the league visited Sydney to meet administrators of the game there. He returned to Auckland on April 7. He said that there was a possibility that the Sydney University team would make a visit along with the Sydney premiership winners.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Visits From Australia/Mr. G. Grey Campbell\u2019s Return\n| page = 16\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=82\n| date = 1934-04-07\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340407.2.125\n| accessdate = 2019-12-02}}</ref> Campbell said that his visit had shown \u201chim how seriously the management committees of the various clubs regarded training. They had more control over the players than did New Zealand. The object... was to get the teams on the ground in the best condition possible. They believed that the team \u201cthat gets in first\u201d gave the others a handicap that took some getting over during the season, and no time and money were spared in preparation\u201d.\n\n==Broadcast of Matches from Carlaw Park==\nThe district radio engineer, Mr. L. L. Macey stated that there was \u201cno ban on the broadcasting of Rugby League football in Auckland\u201d, however the station 1ZB was going to be unable to broadcast matches. The reason being that its application for an extension of broadcasting hours had been turned down by Wellington and as the football was played outside of their broadcast hours they would be unable to carry any coverage.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Football Broadcast/Departmental Attitude/Question of Hours\n| page = 8\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=98\n| date = 1934-04-27\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340427.2.115\n| accessdate = 2019-12-03}}</ref> The decision was met by indignation from New Zealand Rugby League and it was decided to strongly protest and follow up with other action.<ref name=\"annual_meeting\" /> The protest entailed an immediate telegraph to the Postmaster General \u201cagainst unfair discrimination at the cost of the many supporters of the game who paid for licenses as listeners... the executive also was requested to communicate with individual members of Parliament on the subject, and the incoming committee was urged to take further action, if necessary, as it was a matter of urgency to the code and to the general public\u201d. 1ZB had applied two months earlier and was ready to begin broadcasting from the opening weekend of matches however the decision not to allow it had occurred in the days prior to the season opening. Rugby Union was going to be broadcast out of the Broadcasting Boards own funds, and soccer was going to be broadcast through 1YA. Chairman of New Zealand Rugby League, Mr. Cyril Sneddon said \u201cwell, it looks as though there is at the moment a ban, or threatened ban, on Rugby League football \u2013 just another tilt at the code\u201d. There were many other accusations of \u201cstrings being pulled\u201d made by delegates from around the regions.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =League Broadcast/Permission Refused/Discrimination Alleged/Immediate Protest\n| page = 13\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=98\n| date = 1934-04-27\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340427.2.164\n| accessdate = 2019-12-03}}</ref> It was decided by the Hon. Adam Hamilton, Postmaster-General to arrange for the broadcasting of Auckland League football match results. He advised a deputation that he would ascertain if the service could be fitted in with the programme of 1YA or 1YX at a lengthy meeting on the issue where many voices were heard.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Broadcast Issue/Minster Promises Help/Hours Extension Unlikely\n| page = 3\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=122\n| date = 1934-05-25\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340525.2.19\n| accessdate = 2019-12-04}}</ref> Station 1ZB rearranged their Saturday programme so that rugby league broadcasts could be done. They cut out a portion of their Saturday morning programme to make room for the afternoon broadcast of the league. This meant that they did not need to apply to an extension of their hours. The decision was met very favourably by league chairman Campbell who said \u201cwe are very pleased with the result... listeners in the country districts especially will appreciate the action of 1ZB in meeting that has become a widespread demand for the broadcasting of League matches from Carlaw Park\u201d.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Carlaw Park Broadcasts/Adjustment of Programme\n| page = 8\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=127\n| date = 1934-05-31\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340531.2.78\n| accessdate = 2019-12-05}}</ref>\n\n==Life Membership==\nMr. T. Davis was elected a life member of the Auckland Rugby League after he had retired. He had served as a delegate for five years, and for eight years he was the secretary of the junior management committee.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Life Membership Honour\n| page = 16\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=63\n| date = 1934-03-15\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340315.2.140\n| accessdate = 2019-12-01}}</ref>\n\nAt the Auckland Rugby League meeting on May 30 Mr. F. D. Ellis was made a life member of Auckland Rugby League, he had been on the board and served as treasurer for 14 years. He was resigning due to ill health and moving to Australia.<ref name=\"auck_treasurer\">{{cite news \n| title =Auckland Affairs/Resignation of Treasurer\n| page = 18\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=127\n| date = 1934-05-31\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340531.2.148\n| accessdate = 2019-12-05}}</ref>\n\n==Phelan Shield's Debut==\nThe Phelan Shield (which is still competed for today) was first awarded in 1934. It was a \u201chandsome carved shield\u201d presented to [[Auckland Rugby League]] by [[Ted Phelan|Edward John Phelan]] (known commonly as Ted Phelan), one of the trustees of rugby league in Auckland. The shield was played for by the 4 losing teams from the first round of the Roope Rooster and was won by Newton who defeated Ponsonby in the final by 18 points to 10.<ref>{{cite news \n| title = Phelan Shield to Newton\n| page =14\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXXI| issue=21901\n| date = 1934-09-10\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19340910.2.156\n| accessdate = 2020-01-19}}</ref>\n\n==Western Suburbs Tour==\nThe 1934 New South Wales champions [[Wests Tigers|Western Suburbs]] club from Sydney decided to tour New Zealand in September/October. Their first match was with Marist where they won, this was followed by a draw with Newton, a loss to Richmond, a win over Ponsonby, and a loss in the return match with Richmond.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Western Suburbs\u2019 Visit\n| page = 13\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=218\n| date = 1934-09-14\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340914.2.180\n| accessdate = 2019-01-19}}</ref> They were the fifth Australian club to visit New Zealand following on from visits by University, South Sydney, Eastern Suburbs, and St George. They arrived on board the [[SS Mariposa|Mariposa Ship]] on September 22 before commencing a light training run. Four regular first grade players were unable to make the trip but the manager Mr. J. J. White said the side was strengthened by four substitutes \u201cwho, in the opinion of State selectors, with the ten regular, brought the tourists well up to full strength\u201d.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Western Suburbs\u2019 Arrival/Points About the Team\n| page = 19\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=225\n| date = 1934-09-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340922.2.174\n| accessdate = 2020-01-19}}</ref> Just prior to the fourth match with Ponsonby a fire broke out at the Nicholls Brothers Limited premise on Stanley Street with the building being extensively damaged. The boys who played in the curtain-raiser ran from the field to collect their clothes from the dressing shed as they feared the fire may spread to the sheds and offices of Auckland Rugby League.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Factory Fire/Extensive Damage Done\n| page =10 \n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXXI| issue=21922\n| date = 1934-10-04\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19341004.2.41\n| accessdate = 2020-01-19}}</ref> Like many teams who toured New Zealand they spent the last part of their trip touring the Rotorua area taking in the thermal attractions.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\" | List of Matches\n|-\n|\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" |\n! scope=\"col\" | Score\n! scope=\"col\" |\n! scope=\"col\" | Score\n! scope=\"col\" | Venue\n! scope=\"col\" | Attendance\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Western Suburbs Tour Match\n| 22 Sep <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Western Suburbs\u2019 Tour/Marists Narrowly Defeated/Thrilling Opening Match\n| page = 13\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=226\n| date = 1934-09-24\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340924.2.136\n| accessdate = 2020-01-19}}</ref>\n|| Marist|| 19 || Western Suburbs || 21 || Carlaw Park # 1, 3pm||\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Western Suburbs Tour Match\n| 26 Sep <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Newton-Western Suburbs/A Ten-Point Draw\n| page = 22\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=229\n| date = 1934-09-27\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340927.2.190\n| accessdate = 2020-01-19}}</ref>\n|| Newton|| 10 