rt, Ellerslie, Marist A, Marist B, Northcote, Otahuhu, Richmond\n*'''Seven a-side''': Avondale, City, Devonport, Ellerslie, Marist A, Northcote\n\n===Other Notable Matches===\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\" | List of Matches\n|-\n|\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | \n! scope=\"col\" | Score\n! scope=\"col\" | \n! scope=\"col\" | Score\n! scope=\"col\" | Venue\n! scope=\"col\" | Attendance\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Exhibition Match\n| 30 June <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Curtain-Raiser Treat\n| page =13\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| issue=154\n| date = 1934-07-02\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340702.2.149\n| accessdate = 2019-12-05}}</ref>\n|| Mangere|| 11 || Tuakau || 12 || Carlaw Park # 1, 1:30pm\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Exhibition Match\n| 15 September <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Devonport Seniors Win/Defeat of North Auckland\n| page =7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXXI| issue=21908\n| date = 1934-09-18\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19340918.2.38.4\n| accessdate = 2020-01-19}}</ref>\n|| North Auckland|| 11 || Devonport || 17 ||Hikurangi \n|-\n|}\n\n==Representative Fixtures==\nThe first representative fixture of the season was played against Taranaki with L. Hutt being appointed captain. The Taranaki team was being picked by [[Frank Delgrosso]].\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\" | 1934 Auckland Representative Fixtures\n|-\n|\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | \n! scope=\"col\" | Score\n! scope=\"col\" | \n! scope=\"col\" | Score\n! scope=\"col\" | Venue\n! scope=\"col\" | Attendance\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Representative Fixture\n| 30 June <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Inter-Provincial Match\n| page =13\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| issue=154\n| date = 1934-07-02\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340702.2.149\n| accessdate = 2019-12-05}}</ref>\n|| Auckland || 35 || Taranaki || 8 || Carlaw Park # 1, 3pm\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Inter-Provincial\n| 11 August <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Auckland Wins League Rep. Match/Northland\u2019s Strong Bid/Conditions Deciding Factor\n| page = 16\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=190\n| date = 1934-08-13\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340813.2.153\n| accessdate = 2019-12-28}}</ref>\n|| Auckland || 19 || Northland || 12 || Carlaw Park # 1, 3pm\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | North Island v South Island\n| 1 September <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Victory to North/Inter-Island Rugby League/Souths Hold Interval Lead\n| page = 14\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=208\n| date = 1934-09-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340903.2.194\n| accessdate = 2020-01-19}}</ref>\n|| North Island || 36 || South Island || 18 || Carlaw Park, 3pm\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Waitangi Maori Shield\n| 12 September <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Tamaki Team Successful/Defeat of Lower Waikato\n| page =9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXXI| issue=21904\n| date = 1934-09-13\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19340913.2.38.4\n| accessdate = 2020-01-19}}</ref>\n|| Tamaki|| 36 || Lower Waikato || 13 || Carlaw Park\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Inter-Provincial\n| 15 September <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Auckland Defeats South/Visiting Team Weakened\n| page = 13\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXXI| issue=21907\n| date = 1934-09-17\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19340917.2.149.5\n| accessdate = 2020-01-19}}</ref>\n|| Auckland || 35 || South Auckland || 16 || Carlaw Park # 1, 3pm\n|-\n|}\n\n==Annual General Meetings and Club News==\n*[[Auckland Rugby League|Auckland Rugby League Junior Management Committee]] Mr. D Wilkie announced that Mr. T. Davis was resigning as secretary of the junior management after 8 years in the position. It was proposed that he be elected a life member of the Auckland Rugby League, an honour that had only been given to seven people to this point.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Senior Club Meetings\n| page = 19\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=51\n| date = 1934-03-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340301.2.163\n| accessdate = 2019-11-30}}</ref> The Primary Schools Committee announced that its officers were patron, Dr. Pezaro; president, Mr. R. E. Newport; and chairman, Mr. W. Stanley.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Board of Control Affairs\n| page = 18\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=97\n| date = 1934-04-26\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340426.2.170\n| accessdate = 2019-12-03}}</ref>\n\n*[[Auckland Rugby League|Auckland Rugby League Referees Association]] held their annual meeting on March 19. There were over 40 members in attendance and the chairman Mr. A. Ball asked that his resignation be accepted after 11 years in that position and 20 in total as a member. Mr. L. E. Bull was elected president, Mr. A. McCowatt deputy chairman, and Mr. Simpson treasurer.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Referees\u2019 Annual Meeting/Chairman\u2019s Resignation\n| page = 13\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=67\n| date = 1934-03-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340320.2.143\n| accessdate = 2019-12-01}}</ref>\n\n*[[City Rovers|City Rovers Football Club]] held their general meeting at Carlaw Park on Tuesday March 20 at Carlaw Park.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =City Rovers\u2019 Football Club\n| page = 14\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=64\n| date = 1934-03-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340316.2.162.2\n| accessdate = 2019-12-01}}</ref> A good attendance was recorded and fourteen new members were elected, including four senior players. The financial statement showed a credit of \u00a370 and a profit on the season of over \u00a323. Mr. R. B. Ashby was elected patron, and Mr. L. McDonald the president.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =City Rovers Club\n| page = 19\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=69\n| date = 1934-03-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340322.2.163\n| accessdate = 2019-12-02}}</ref>\n\n*[[North Shore Albions|Devonport United]] held their annual meeting over Anthony\u2019s Tearooms, Devonport on Wednesday March 21.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Devonport United League Football Club\n| page = 21\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=65\n| date = 1934-03-17\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340317.2.178.5\n| accessdate = 2019-12-01}}</ref> The meeting was presided over by Mr. Arch Ferguson and saw 80 members and supporters in attendance. The club had cash and assets amounting to \u00a359. Mr. A. W. D. Meiklejohn was elected patron, Mr. J. Donald president, and Mr. A. Ferguson vice-president. Mr. C. McSweeney donated a trophy to be used as the club decided and Mr. Wouldes donated one for the most improved senior player.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Devonport United Club\n| page = 18\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=71\n| date = 1934-03-24\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340324.2.139\n| accessdate = 2019-12-02}}</ref> At the Auckland Rugby League Board of Control meeting on May 16 [[North Shore Albions|Devonport]] applied for and were granted permission to play their match versus [[Richmond Bulldogs|Richmond]] on the North Shore in aid of the [[Noel Crump]] fund.<ref name=\"control_board\">{{cite news \n| title =Auckland Control Board\n| page = 18\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=115\n| date = 1934-05-17\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340517.2.167\n| accessdate = 2019-12-04}}</ref> He was raising funds to go to the [[1934 British Empire Games]] where he would later compete and win a bronze medal. Prior to the round 6 matches Devonport advised the league that Mr. A. Laing, sen., had been appointed coach and selector to succeed A. W. Seagar who would revert back to being a playing member only.<ref name=\"auck_treasurer\" />\n\n*[[Ellerslie Eagles|Ellerslie United League Football Club]] held their annual meeting at the Club\u2019s Training Shed, Findlay St, Ellerslie on Wednesday, March 14.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Ellerslie United League Football Club\n| page = 19\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=59\n| date = 1934-03-10\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340310.2.193.8\n| accessdate = 2019-11-30}}</ref> There was a large attendance with the balance sheet shown to be in a satisfactory position. Mr. J. W. Jordan MP. was elected patron, Mr. J. McInnarny president, and Mr. F. Chapman club captain. Mr. G. Chapman, jun., was unanimously elected an honorary life member of the club.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Ellerslie United Club\n| page = 16\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=63\n| date = 1934-03-15\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340315.2.140\n| accessdate = 2019-12-01}}</ref> Proposals for the floodlighting of the Ellerslie Domain were discussed by the Ellerslie Domain Board and representatives of the local sports bodies on May 15. It was recommended by the Auckland Electric-Power Board \u201cthat not less than two lights be installed. The Power Board would be prepared to install the lights for \u00a314 on condition that the Domain Board would undertake to pay a flat rate of \u00a32 15s per lamp per annum, inclusive of power and maintenance, and accept the arrangement for not less than five years\u201d.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Ellerslie Domain/Proposals for Lighting\n| page = 14\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXXI| issue=21801\n| date = 1934-05-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19340516.2.174\n| accessdate = 2019-12-16}}</ref>\n\n*[[Glenora Bears|Glenora Rugby League Football Club]] held their annual meeting at the Glen Eden Town Hall.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Glenora League Football Club\n| page = 20\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=50\n| date = 1934-02-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340228.2.216.7\n| accessdate = 2019-11-30}}</ref> A \u201cgood gathering of supporters and followers\u201d attended with Mr. A. J. Routley elected Patron, and Mr W. McNeil chairman.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Glenora Annual Meeting\n| page = 14\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=55\n| date = 1934-03-06\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340306.2.172\n| accessdate = 2019-11-30}}</ref> Trainings were being held at the Glen Eden Recreation Ground.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Glenora League Football\n| page = 20\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=62\n| date = 1934-03-14\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340314.2.193.1\n| accessdate = 2019-12-01}}</ref> Glenora requested that a referee be sent to their club to address the players on the finer points of play so the Auckland Rugby League Referees Association agreed to send Mr. S. Billman to visit the Glen Eden club.<ref name=\"affairs_refs\" /> The league made a special grant towards the Glenora club towards ground expenses. They advised the league that they had signed over 55 new players in the 1934 season and were making good progress in the Glen Eden district.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Control Board Affairs\n| page = 16\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXIV| issue=145\n| date = 1934-06-21\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340621.2.153\n| accessdate = 2019-12-05}}</ref>\n\n*[[Mangere Rugby League Football Club]] were asked to compel spectators to stand back on the bank at games staged in Mangere.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Junior Board Affairs\n| page = 15\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=144\n| date = 1934-06-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340620.2.151\n| accessdate = 2019-12-05}}</ref>\n\n*[[Manukau Magpies|Manukau League Football Club]] held their annual meeting in Kelvin Hall, Queen Street, Onehunga on Monday, March 19.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Manukau League Football Club\n| page = 21\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=65\n| date = 1934-03-17\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340317.2.178.5\n| accessdate = 2019-12-01}}</ref> The Onehunga Borough Council at a meeting on April 3 stated that the Manukau league club could use its recreation reserve provided it laid a portion of the concrete floor in its new shed, and a water meter was installed.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Onehunga Council\n| page = 3\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=79\n| date = 1934-04-04\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340404.2.21\n| accessdate = 2019-12-02}}</ref> On April 14 a \u201cBig Maori Carnival and Athletic Sports\u201d event was held at the Onehunga Recreation Ground. It included senior league matches.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Big Maori Carnival and Athletic Sports\n| page = 14\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=87\n| date = 1934-04-13\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340413.2.181.7\n| accessdate = 2019-12-02}}</ref> After the June 30 round of matches a member mentioned at a Board of Control meeting that facilities continued to be lacking at the Manukau ground with no lines being marked, no flags, and the goal posts were down at one end. The match still took place anyway.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Affairs of Referees\n| page = 14\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=155\n| date = 1934-07-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340703.2.155\n| accessdate = 2019-12-06}}</ref>\n\n*[[Marist Saints|Marist Brothers Old Boys League Football Club]] held their annual meeting in the League Rooms, Courthouse Lane on Thursday 22, March.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Marist Old Boys\u2019 Rugby League Football Club\n| page = 18\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=67\n| date = 1934-03-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340320.2.168.3\n| accessdate = 2019-12-01}}</ref> Nearly one hundred members were in attendance to hear that the club was in a healthy financial position. Reverend Dr. Liston, Bishop of Auckland was elected patron, Mr. E. Lahman president, and Mr. J. Kirwan secretary.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Marist Old Boys\u2019 Club\n| page = 10\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=70\n| date = 1934-03-23\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340323.2.154\n| accessdate = 2019-12-02}}</ref> Marist advertised for a special general meeting to be held at the Chamber of Commerce rooms on Swanson Street on Monday, 28.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Marist Old Boys Club\n| page = 20\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=121\n| date = 1934-05-24\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340524.2.170\n| accessdate = 2019-12-04}}</ref> It turned out that the voting at their original meeting was declared void as unqualified members had voted. Mr. Cyril Sneddon, the president of New Zealand Rugby League was invited to attend and the following officers were elected: patron, Reverend Dr. Liston; president, Mr. J. Sayegh; club captain, Mr. H. Brisbane; hon secretary, Mr. J. Kirwan; Mr. O. Robertson.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Marist O.B. Club/Annual Meeting Re-Held\n| page = 13\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=125\n| date = 1934-05-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340529.2.131\n| accessdate = 2019-12-04}}</ref> In round 6 eight of the senior Marist players (W. Hassan, C. Dunn, D. Herring, the 3 Shultz brothers, and C. list) refused to appear. They were in a dispute with the club over \u201cwhether a porting of expenditure should apply to senior players alone or be devoted to general club services, including juniors\u201d. Despite fielding many juniors the team still won their match. Hassan transferred to the rugby code and played for Marist rugby club the following weekend.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Football Dispute/Marist League Club\n| page = 3\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=134\n| date = 1934-06-08\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340608.2.14\n| accessdate = 2019-12-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite news \n| title =Marist Club Overruled\n| page = 16\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXIV| issue=145\n| date = 1934-06-21\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340621.2.153\n| accessdate = 2019-12-05}}</ref> The Marist club tried to suspend the players involved but the New Zealand Rugby League Council said that the players in question could apply for transfers to other clubs. Marist appealed this decision and when four of the players did apply for transfers the Marist club refused this.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Auckland Affairs/Successful Junior Appeal/Marist Club Repercussions\n| page = 17\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=157\n| date = 1934-07-05\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340705.2.134\n| accessdate = 2019-12-06}}</ref>\n\n*[[Mt Albert Lions|Mt. Albert United Rugby League Football Club]] held their annual meeting in the King George Hall, Mt Albert Terminus on Thursday, March 8.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =The Mount Albert United Rugby Football Club\n| page = 18\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=55\n| date = 1934-03-06\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340306.2.215.4\n| accessdate = 2019-11-30}}</ref> It was their sixth annual meeting and it was commented by the president Mr. J. Eccles that the club was in a sound financial position. The Mayor of Mount Albert Mr. Ferner was elected Patron, Mr. A. S. Richards M.P. was elected vice-patron, Mr. J. Eccles president, and Mr. R. Wilson secretary and treasurer. Mr. W. F. Clarke who had held office for the first six years of the club tendered his resignation and as a mark of appreciation was elected a life member.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Mount Albert Club\n| page = 11\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=58\n| date = 1934-03-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340309.2.146\n| accessdate = 2019-11-30}}</ref> They held their annual practice at Fowld\u2019s Park, Morningside on April 7. Prior to this in previous seasons they had held practices and games at the ground at Springleigh Ave and at Fowld\u2019s Park which had previously been known as Morningside Reserve but in July 1933 was renamed Fowld\u2019s Park in honour of the honourable Sir George Fowlds.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Fowld\u2019s Park\n| page = 6\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXIV| issue=168\n| date = 1934-07-19\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19330719.2.61\n| accessdate = 2019-12-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite news \n| title =Mt. Albert United Rugby League Football Club\n| page = 22\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=80\n| date = 1934-04-05\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340405.2.173.3\n| accessdate = 2019-12-02}}</ref> A special general meeting was to be held at Fowld\u2019s Park on Saturday, April 21 regarding the changing of the club\u2019s colours.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Mt. Albert United Rugby League Football Club\n| page = 24\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=92\n| date = 1934-04-19\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340419.2.186.3\n| accessdate = 2019-12-02}}</ref>\n\n*New Lynn Rugby League Football Club held a special meeting at the Old Post Office, Totara Avenue on March 22.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =League Football, Special Meeting\n| page = 18\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=68\n| date = 1934-03-21\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340321.2.173.1\n| accessdate = 2019-12-02}}</ref>\n\n*[[Newton Rangers|Newton Rangers Football Club]] held their annual meeting at Grey\u2019s Buildings, Courthouse Lane on Monday March 12.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Newton Rangers Football Club\n| page = 19\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=53\n| date = 1934-03-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340303.2.180.5\n| accessdate = 2019-11-30}}</ref> The meeting was presided over by Mr. E. W. Taylor with over seventy members and supporters in attendance. Mr. D. Wilkie, chairman of the junior management committee was also in attendance. Their report touched on the playing improvement of the previous season and the balance sheet showed a credit of \u00a319 10/. Mr. Matt. Hooper was elected patron, Mr W. Monteith vice-patron, and Mr. J. A. Lee MP president. Notably Mr. P. Henry was elected treasurer for the 17th year.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Newton Rangers\u2019 Club\n| page = 13\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=61\n| date = 1934-03-13\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340313.2.132\n| accessdate = 2019-12-01}}</ref> Mr. A. J. McGregor (\u201cDugie\u201d) was unanimously elected as the sole selector and coach of the senior team with Mr. A. McLeod to fill the same role for the reserve team. Mr. A Middleton was chosen as the trainer and Mr. Turner the property steward. Before the season started the secretary received a cablegram suggesting that Roy Hardgrave would be returning to New Zealand to play for his old club. He left Newton to go and play for St. Helens in England in 1929 and had spent five seasons there.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Contract Ended/Footballer\u2019s Return\n| page = 8\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=67\n| date = 1934-03-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340320.2.104\n| accessdate = 2019-12-01}}</ref> He arrived back in Auckland on June 25 aboard the Aorangi with his wife and four year old daughter. He was met at the wharf by players and officials of the Newton club.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Footballer\u2019s Return/Roy Hardgrave Back/Keen to Play in Auckland\n| page = 9\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=148\n| date = 1934-06-25\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340625.2.124\n| accessdate = 2019-12-05}}</ref> A \u201cWelcome Home\u201d dance was held for Hardgrave by the Newton club with over 500 people in attendance.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Newton Rangers Club/Welcome Home to Hardgrave\n| page = 14\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=150\n| date = 1934-06-27\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340627.2.129\n| accessdate = 2019-12-05}}</ref> During the season several prominent Newton players were granted transfers to Mt Albert and this was appealed by the Newton club, though the New Zealand Rugby League Council heard the case and dismissed it.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Appeal Dismissed\n| page = 9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXXI| issue=21887\n| date = 1934-08-24\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19340824.2.32.9\n| accessdate = 2020-01-19}}</ref>\n\n*[[Northcote Tigers|Northcote and Birkenhead Ramblers Football Club]] held their annual meeting at the Buffalo\u2019s Hall, Northcote on Tuesday March 13.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Rugby League\n| page = 16\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXXI| issue=21746\n| date = 1934-03-10\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19340310.2.179.2\n| accessdate = 2019-11-30}}</ref> The Northcote Borough Council granted the use of the municipal ground at Stafford Park to the Northcote Rugby League team and the Northcote rugby team on alternate Saturday\u2019s.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Northcote Borough Council\n| page = 11\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=74\n| date = 1934-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340328.2.120\n| accessdate = 2019-12-02}}</ref>\n\n*[[Otahuhu Leopards|Otahuhu Rugby League Football Club]] held their annual meeting in the local Gas Company\u2019s hall. The balance-sheet showed that the club was in a sound financial position. [[Walter William Massey|Mr. W. W. Massey, MP]] was elected patron, Mr. J. Nicholson elected president, and Mr. J. Clark elected chairman.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Otahuhu Club\n| page = 16\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=63\n| date = 1934-03-15\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340315.2.140\n| accessdate = 2019-12-01}}</ref> On July 5 the Otahuhu Borough Council\u2019s parks committee reported that it had awarded a contract to install floodlights at a cost of \u00a350 at Sturgess Park. The Otahuhu league club had been given use of the park along with the Otahuhu rugby club, and they tended to alternate the use of it. Both clubs were given permission to collect a charge from spectators on two upcoming match days each provided that the proceeds of one day are divided between the parks committee and charity.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Local Bodies/Otahuhu\n| page = 3\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=158\n| date = 1934-07-06\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340706.2.30\n| accessdate = 2019-12-06}}</ref>\n\n*[[Papakura Sea Eagles|Papakura Rugby League Football Club]] They applied for use of Prince Edward Park for the upcoming season and the Papakura Town Board asked for tenders for use of the ground.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Papakura\n| page = 9\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=49\n| date = 1934-02-27\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340227.2.139\n| accessdate = 2019-11-30}}</ref> The chairman of the reserves committee, Mr. G. W. Kerr said that the previous season two applications had been received for the use of the ground and the board had difficulty in deciding which application to grant.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Papakura Interests/Lease of Playing Area/Tenders to be Called\n| page = 5\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXXI| issue=21736\n| date = 1934-02-27\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19340227.2.21\n| accessdate = 2019-11-30}}</ref> The decision was eventually made for them when no other tenderers came forward and the ground was granted to Papakura Rugby League for \u201ctwo guineas for Saturday play\u201d.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Papakura Town Board\n| page = 3\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=61\n| date = 1934-03-13\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340313.2.17\n| accessdate = 2019-12-31}}</ref> The club was concerned about loss of junior clubs best players to the senior grade clubs.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Papakura Club\n| page = 19\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=51\n| date = 1934-03-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340301.2.163\n| accessdate = 2019-11-30}}</ref> At their annual meeting which was held on March 1 Mr. S. H. Godden was in the chair and Mr. E. C. Foote was elected Patron, and Godden was elected President.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Papakura Football\n| page = 10\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=52\n| date = 1934-03-02\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340302.2.146\n| accessdate = 2019-11-30}}</ref> In mid April the Papakura club advised Auckland Rugby League that Mr. T. Harrison had been appointed to its committee, other officers appointed were G. Wilton as chairman, A. L. Lewis as secretary, and V. Ashby as treasurer.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Junior Management\n| page = 14\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=91\n| date = 1934-04-18\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340418.2.137\n| accessdate = 2019-12-02}}</ref> The balance sheet showed a small credit. Their annual report stated that they had a membership of 70 and had 23 honorary members.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Papakura Club\u2019s Officers\n| page = 9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXXI| issue=21740\n| date = 1934-03-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19340303.2.39.4\n| accessdate = 2019-11-30}}</ref> The New Zealand Herald reported on the Round 1 Second Grade match between Papakura and Ellerslie, played at Prince Edward Park. The match was won by Papakura 11\u20130.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Play at Papakura\n| page = 13\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXXI| issue=21793\n| date = 1934-05-07\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19340507.2.157.2\n| accessdate = 2019-12-03}}</ref> Mr. Billman from the Referees Association reported that there were 79 players and officials at a training night that he had been requested to attend. He said it was a pleasure to note the enthusiasm display.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Affairs of Referees\n| page = 14\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=149\n| date = 1934-06-26\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340626.2.154\n| accessdate = 2019-12-05}}</ref> On June 30 the fifth grade teams bus broke down on the way to Victoria Park and the match was called off and awarded to Ponsonby. After the reason for their late arrival was explained it was decided to replay the match at a later date.<ref name=\"jb_affairs\" />\n\n*[[Point Chevalier Pirates|Point Chevalier League Football Club]] held their annual meeting at the Point Chevalier Sailing Club Hall on Wednesday, March 21.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Pt. Chevalier League Football Club\n| page = 21\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=65\n| date = 1934-03-17\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340317.2.178.5\n| accessdate = 2019-12-01}}</ref>\n\n*[[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United Football Club]] held their 23rd annual meeting at Leys Institute, Ponsonby on Tuesday March 6.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Annual Meeting, Ponsonby United Football Club\n| page = 20\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=50\n| date = 1934-02-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340228.2.216.7\n| accessdate = 2019-11-30}}</ref> The 24th report in the clubs history was submitted and stated that despite some misfortunes the senior team was very young and showed promising signs especially under the coaching of ex-international [[Frank Delgrosso]]. Brian Riley won an award for the most improved back, and L. Hutt was chosen as the best forward. The club had suffered a financial loss for the 1933 season but had been able through its credit building fund to advance a loan to the Auckland Rugby League of \u00a3150 to assist in the grandstand development scheme at Carlaw Park. They elected Mr. A. H. McKeown as patron, Mr. S. McDonald as president, and Mr. C. J. W. Taylor as treasurer.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Ponsonby United Club\n| page = 10\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=80\n| date = 1934-04-06\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340406.2.129\n| accessdate = 2019-12-02}}</ref> At the May 16 Board of Control meeting of Auckland Rugby League Ponsonby notified them that Mr. L. Riley, the international player had become a coach at Northcote, and that Mr. A. Philburn had been appointed to the Ponsonby Club committee in succession to Mr. R. Allen.<ref name=\"control_board\" />\n\n*[[Richmond Bulldogs|Richmond Rovers Football Club]] held their annual meeting at the Gaiety Hall, Surrey Crescent on Monday March 5.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Richmond Rovers Football Club\n| page = 19\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=53\n| date = 1934-03-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340303.2.180.5\n| accessdate = 2019-11-30}}</ref> There was a large attendance of players and members with the annual report and balance sheet showing that the club was in a sound financial position. Mr. W. J. Holdsworth was elected Patron, Mr. B. W. Davis president, and Mr. W. A. Swift chairman. Mr. Davis was celebrating his 21st year with the club and it was proposed to mark the occasion with a presentation. There were 28 new playing members registered during the evening.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Richmond Rovers Club\n| page = 14\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXV| issue=55\n| date = 1934-03-06\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19340306.2.172\n| accessdate = 2019-11-30}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.aucklandleague.co.nz/ Auckland Rugby League Official Site]\n\n[[Category:Auckland Rugby League seasons]]\n[[Category:Rugby league in Auckland]]\n[[Category:Rugby league governing bodies in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Rugby league]]\n", "name_user": "Schwede66", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixeddashesusing ascript, date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1934_Auckland_Rugby_League_season"}
{"title_page": "Tess Liem", "text_new": "'''Tess Liem''' is a [[Canada|Canadian]] poet from [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]], who published her debut poetry collection ''Obits'' in 2018.<ref>[https://quillandquire.com/review/amateurs-at-love/ \"Reviews: Amateurs at Love, Obits, Ruba\u2019iyat for the Time of Apricots\"]. ''[[Quill & Quire]]'', January 2019.</ref> The book was named one of the year's best Canadian poetry collections by [[CBC Arts]],<ref name=cbc>[https://www.cbc.ca/books/the-best-canadian-poetry-of-2018-1.4945337 \"The best Canadian poetry of 2018\"]. [[CBC Books]], December 13, 2018.</ref> and won the [[Gerald Lampert Award]] from the [[League of Canadian Poets]] in 2019.<ref>[https://quillandquire.com/omni/tess-liem-stevie-howell-win-2019-book-awards-for-poetry/ \"Tess Liem, Stevie Howell win 2019 Book Awards for poetry\"]. ''[[Quill & Quire]]'', June 10, 2019.</ref>\n\nThe book was also nominated for a [[Lambda Literary Award]] for [[Lambda Literary Award for Lesbian Poetry|Lesbian Poetry]] at the [[31st Lambda Literary Awards]],<ref>[https://quillandquire.com/omni/vivek-shraya-joshua-whitehead-among-10-canadian-finalists-for-lambda-literary-awards/ \"Vivek Shraya, Joshua Whitehead among Canadian finalists for Lambda Literary Awards\"]. ''[[Quill & Quire]]'', March 7, 2019.</ref> and was longlisted for the [[Pat Lowther Award]].<ref>[https://quillandquire.com/omni/league-of-canadian-poets-announces-2019-book-awards-longlists/ \"League of Canadian Poets announces 2019 Book Awards longlists\"]. ''[[Quill & Quire]]'', April 1, 2019.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Liem, Tess}}\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian women writers]]\n[[Category:Canadian women poets]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from Canada]]\n[[Category:LGBT poets]]\n[[Category:Writers from Montreal]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{Canada-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Tess Liem''' is a [[Canada|Canadian]] poet from [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]], who published her debut poetry collection ''Obits'' in 2018.<ref>[https://quillandquire.com/review/amateurs-at-love/ \"Reviews: Amateurs at Love, Obits, Ruba\u2019iyat for the Time of Apricots\"]. ''[[Quill & Quire]]'', January 2019.</ref> The book was named one of the year's best Canadian poetry collections by [[CBC Arts]],<ref name=cbc>[https://www.cbc.ca/books/the-best-canadian-poetry-of-2018-1.4945337 \"The best Canadian poetry of 2018\"]. [[CBC Books]], December 13, 2018.</ref> and won the [[Gerald Lampert Award]] from the [[League of Canadian Poets]] in 2019.<ref>[https://quillandquire.com/omni/tess-liem-stevie-howell-win-2019-book-awards-for-poetry/ \"Tess Liem, Stevie Howell win 2019 Book Awards for poetry\"]. ''[[Quill & Quire]]'', June 10, 2019.</ref>\n\nThe book was also nominated for a [[Lambda Literary Award]] for [[Lambda Literary Award for Lesbian Poetry|Lesbian Poetry]] at the [[31st Lambda Literary Awards]],<ref>[https://quillandquire.com/omni/vivek-shraya-joshua-whitehead-among-10-canadian-finalists-for-lambda-literary-awards/ \"Vivek Shraya, Joshua Whitehead among Canadian finalists for Lambda Literary Awards\"]. ''[[Quill & Quire]]'', March 7, 2019.</ref> and was longlisted for the [[Pat Lowther Award]].<ref>[https://quillandquire.com/omni/league-of-canadian-poets-announces-2019-book-awards-longlists/ \"League of Canadian Poets announces 2019 Book Awards longlists\"]. ''[[Quill & Quire]]'', April 1, 2019.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Liem, Tess}}\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian women writers]]\n[[Category:Canadian women poets]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from Canada]]\n[[Category:LGBT poets]]\n[[Category:Writers from Montreal]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{Canada-writer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe",